class Solution {
    public long minSumSquareDiff(int[] nums1, int[] nums2, int k1, int k2) {
        int n = nums1.length;
        long[] diffs = new long[n];
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            diffs[i] = Math.abs((long) nums1[i] - nums2[i]);
        }
        Arrays.sort(diffs);
        long total = k1 + k2;
        long res = 0;
        for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            long d = diffs[i];
            if (total >= d) {
                total -= d;
                res += d * d;
            } else {
                res += (d - total) * (d - total);
                break;
            }
        }
        return res;
    }
}
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n log n)
space complexity: O(n)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The main approach is to first calculate the absolute differences between corresponding elements in the two input arrays, sort these differences in ascending order, and then iteratively reduce the largest differences using the available modifications (k1 + k2). The key strength is that it efficiently utilizes the total number of modifications allowed to minimize the sum of squared differences.
